**Question 8:**

Contract of `mergeSeedEntries` — pure or side-effect-aware?

- **(a) Pure**: `(prev, seed, pendingIds) => DraftEntry[]`. Caller separately handles cancelling timers for ids that disappeared.
- **(b) Returns metadata**: `(prev, seed, pendingIds) => { entries, droppedPendingIds }` so caller knows which timers to clear.

The caller can derive droppedPendingIds itself trivially (`pendingIds − seedIds`), so (b) doesn't save much.

My recommendation: **(a) pure**. The function answers one question — "what should `entries` be?" — and timer lifecycle stays owned by the hook. Effect body becomes:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  if (lastSeededKeyRef.current === seedKey) return;
  lastSeededKeyRef.current = seedKey;

  const seedIds = new Set(seedEntries.map(e => e.id));
  for (const [id, timer] of persistTimers.current) {
    if (!seedIds.has(id)) {
      clearTimeout(timer);
      persistTimers.current.delete(id);
    }
  }
  const pendingIds = new Set(persistTimers.current.keys());
  setEntries(prev => mergeSeedEntries(prev, seedEntries, pendingIds));
}, [seedKey, seedEntries]);
```

Agree on (a)?

